    "id": "samyaktva",
    "sanskrit": "सम्यक्त्व",
    "title": "Samyaktva",
    "category": "Foundation",
    "tagline": "Right faith — the prerequisite that makes every other practice meaningful.",
    "summary": "Samyaktva is rational faith in the true nature of reality. Without it, all rituals, fasting, and devotion are hollow. It is the starting point of genuine spiritual progress in Jainism.",
    "full_content": "Samyaktva — right faith or right belief — is the single most important concept in Jain philosophy for one reason: without it, nothing else counts. You can fast for days, recite mantras for hours, donate millions — but if you lack Samyaktva, you have not taken the first step on the path.\n\nSo what is it? Samyaktva is the firm conviction in the true nature of the soul and reality as described by the Tirthankars. It means accepting, without doubt, that the soul exists, that karma binds it, and that liberation is possible through right knowledge, right faith, and right conduct.\n\nBut Samyaktva is not blind belief. It is not faith because your parents told you. It is rational conviction born from understanding. The Jain tradition identifies three markers of Samyaktva: freedom from doubt (nihshankita), freedom from desire for worldly pleasures as the goal (nishkankshita), and freedom from disgust toward the path (nirvichikitsa).\n\nThere are also five types of wrong belief that destroy Samyaktva: Ekantavada (one-sided thinking), Viparit (perverse understanding), Vinaya (worshipping false gods out of social obligation), Samshaya (doubt about the teachings), and Ajnana (ignorance or indifference).\n\nSamyaktva is considered so critical that the Jain tradition holds a soul with right faith — even without extensive knowledge or perfect conduct — is on a higher spiritual plane than one with vast knowledge but wrong belief. It is the seed. Everything else grows from it.",
