    "tagline": "The soul — not a metaphor, not a belief, but the conscious core of every living being.",
    "summary": "Jiva is the soul — a conscious, non-material entity that experiences, perceives, and persists through the architecture of time. It is the fundamental unit of existence in Jain metaphysics.",
    "full_content": "In Jain philosophy, the Jiva — the soul — is not a poetic idea or a comforting belief. It is a metaphysical reality, as fundamental to Jain cosmology as atoms are to physics. Every living being, from the most complex human to the simplest one-sensed organism in earth, water, fire, or air, possesses a Jiva.\n\nThe Jiva has certain inherent qualities: infinite knowledge (keval jnana), infinite perception (keval darshan), infinite bliss (sukha), and infinite energy (virya). But in its bound state — which is the condition of every soul not yet liberated — these qualities are obscured by karma. Think of it like the sun behind clouds: the sun's luminosity hasn't diminished, but we can't see it.\n\nA critical distinction in Jain philosophy: the soul is not the body, not the mind, not the karma attached to it. The soul is the permanent observer in a temporary universe. While the physical form undergoes entropy and the mental form undergoes fluctuation, the Jiva remains constant.\n\nJivas are classified by the number of senses they possess. One-sensed beings (ekendriya) like earth, water, fire, air, and plant bodies have only the sense of touch. Two-sensed beings add taste. Three-sensed add smell. Four-sensed add sight. Five-sensed beings like humans and many animals have all five senses, plus the capacity for rational thought.\n\nThis classification has profound ethical implications. Because every being has a soul, every act of harm — no matter how small the creature — has karmic consequences. This is why Jain non-violence extends far beyond not killing animals. It encompasses a reverence for all forms of life.",
