    "summary": "Ajiva encompasses all non-living substances in the universe: matter, space, time, and the principles of motion and rest. Together with Jiva, it forms the complete inventory of reality.",
    "full_content": "If Jiva is the conscious actor, Ajiva is everything else — the stage, the props, the lighting, and the laws that govern the performance. Ajiva literally means 'non-soul,' and it encompasses five categories of non-living substance.\n\nPudgala (Matter) is the only Ajiva substance that has form, color, taste, smell, and touch. It includes everything physical — bodies, food, air, karma particles. Yes, in Jain philosophy, karma is material. It is not an abstract spiritual ledger but actual subtle matter that binds to the soul.\n\nDharma Dravya (Principle of Motion) is not dharma in the moral sense. It is a cosmic substance that makes movement possible. Without it, nothing could move — not atoms, not souls. Think of it like water that enables a fish to swim. The water doesn't push the fish, but without it, swimming is impossible.\n\nAdharma Dravya (Principle of Rest) is the complement — the substance that makes stillness possible. Without it, nothing could stop moving.\n\nAkasha (Space) provides the container for everything to exist in. It is infinite, but divided into lokakash (occupied space where souls, matter, and the other substances exist) and alokakash (empty space beyond, containing nothing).\n\nKala (Time) enables change and continuity. Without time, no transformation could occur — no birth, no death, no karmic fruition.\n\nThis framework is remarkable for its completeness. Jain metaphysics doesn't just account for the visible world — it provides substances to explain why motion exists, why stillness exists, why change happens. Every aspect of reality has a corresponding substance.",
