    "id": "six-dravyas",
    "sanskrit": "षड् द्रव्य",
    "title": "Six Dravyas",
    "category": "Soul & Reality",
    "tagline": "The six eternal substances — Jainism's complete inventory of everything that exists.",
    "summary": "The Six Dravyas are the building blocks of Jain metaphysics: Soul, Matter, Principle of Motion, Principle of Rest, Space, and Time. Together, they account for every phenomenon in the universe.",
    "full_content": "Jain philosophy proposes that everything in the universe — every phenomenon, every experience, every particle — can be accounted for by exactly six eternal substances called Dravyas. Nothing exists outside this framework.\n\nThe six are: Jiva (Soul), Pudgala (Matter), Dharma (Medium of Motion), Adharma (Medium of Rest), Akasha (Space), and Kala (Time). Each is eternal — never created, never destroyed — but each undergoes constant modification.\n\nThis is one of Jainism's most sophisticated insights: a substance can be permanent in its essential nature while being impermanent in its modes. Gold remains gold, but it can be shaped into a ring, a necklace, or a coin. The gold (substance) persists; the forms (modes) change. Similarly, the soul persists eternally, but its embodied forms — human, animal, celestial, hellish — are temporary modes.\n\nOf the six, only Jiva possesses consciousness. Only Pudgala has physical form. The other four — Dharma, Adharma, Akasha, and Kala — are formless. They cannot be perceived by the senses. They are known only through scriptural knowledge and inference.\n\nDharma and Adharma are perhaps the most unique contributions of Jain metaphysics to Indian philosophy. No other system posits separate substances for the possibility of motion and rest. They don't cause motion or stillness — they enable it. The distinction is crucial. A bus enables travel, but it doesn't decide where you go.\n\nThe Six Dravyas give Jainism a complete ontology — a theory of what exists. Every question about reality can be answered within this framework, from 'why do things move?' to 'what happens to the soul after death?'",
