    "tagline": "The four destinies — where the soul goes when it leaves this body.",
    "summary": "Gati describes the four possible states of existence for the soul: human, celestial, hellish, and animal/plant. The soul cycles through these based on accumulated karma.",
    "full_content": "When a soul leaves one body, where does it go? Jain philosophy answers with crystalline precision: there are exactly four destinations, called Gatis.\n\nDev Gati (Celestial existence) — birth among the devas, beings of great power and pleasure. But this is not heaven in the Abrahamic sense. It is temporary. Celestial beings enjoy extraordinary lifespans and abilities, but they are not liberated. When their celestial karma expires, they are reborn elsewhere.\n\nManushya Gati (Human existence) — the most valuable birth. Not because humans are the most powerful (devas are), or because human life is the most pleasant (it isn't). It is valuable because only from human existence can a soul achieve liberation. The celestial beings are too intoxicated by pleasure. Hellish beings are too overwhelmed by suffering. Animals lack the rational capacity. Only humans have the precise balance of suffering, intellect, and moral capacity needed to walk the path.\n\nTiryanch Gati (Animal and plant existence) — this encompasses an enormous range, from five-sensed animals down to one-sensed beings like earth, water, fire, air bodies, and plants. The vast majority of souls in the universe are in this state.\n\nNarak Gati (Hellish existence) — birth in one of the seven hells, where the soul endures intense suffering. Like celestial existence, this is temporary. The duration depends on the severity of accumulated karma.\n\nThe soul has been cycling through these four gatis since beginningless time. There is no first birth. The cycle continues until the soul accumulates the right karma to achieve human birth, encounters the right teachings, develops Samyaktva, and progresses toward liberation.\n\nThis framework dissolves the idea that humans are fundamentally different from other beings. The same soul that is human today may have been a celestial being, an animal, or a hellish being in previous lives.",
