    "id": "nav-tattvas",
    "sanskrit": "नव तत्त्व",
    "title": "Nav Tattvas",
    "category": "Karma System",
    "tagline": "The nine realities — the complete map of how karma works.",
    "summary": "The Nav Tattvas are nine fundamental categories that explain the soul's bondage and liberation: Jiva, Ajiva, Punya, Papa, Asrav, Samvar, Bandh, Nirjara, and Moksha.",
    "full_content": "If the Six Dravyas tell you what exists, the Nav Tattvas tell you what happens — specifically, how the soul gets bound by karma and how it can free itself. These nine categories are the complete operating manual for the karmic system.\n\nJiva (Soul) and Ajiva (Non-soul) establish the two fundamental categories of existence. Everything is one or the other.\n\nAsrav (Influx) is the process by which karma particles flow toward the soul. Every activity of mind, speech, and body creates vibrations that attract karma. This influx is happening constantly, in every moment of embodied existence.\n\nBandh (Bondage) is what happens when those karma particles actually bind to the soul. The type of karma that binds depends on the nature of the activity; the intensity of bondage depends on the passions (kashays) accompanying it.\n\nPunya (Merit) and Papa (Sin) are the two qualities of karma. Punya results from virtuous activities and brings pleasant karmic fruit — good health, wealth, favorable birth. Papa results from harmful activities and brings suffering. But here's the critical insight: both are bondage. Even punya is a chain — a golden chain, but a chain nonetheless. Liberation requires freedom from both.\n\nSamvar (Stoppage) is the process of stopping new karma from flowing in. Through self-discipline, careful conduct, and control of passions, the soul can reduce and eventually halt the influx.\n\nNirjara (Shedding) is the process of destroying previously accumulated karma. This happens naturally as karma matures and bears fruit, but can be accelerated through austerities and meditation.\n\nMoksha (Liberation) is the ultimate goal — the state in which all karma has been destroyed and the soul exists in its pure, infinite nature forever. No more birth. No more death. No more bondage.\n\nThe Nav Tattvas are not abstract philosophy. They are a diagnostic framework. At any moment, you can ask: What karma am I attracting? What is binding to me? Am I stopping the influx? Am I shedding what's already there?",
