    "id": "karma",
    "sanskrit": "कर्म",
    "title": "Karma",
    "category": "Karma System",
    "tagline": "Not a cosmic scorecard — actual subtle matter that clings to the soul.",
    "summary": "In Jainism, karma is not metaphorical. It is real, material particles that bind to the soul through our actions, thoughts, and intentions, obscuring its inherent infinite qualities.",
    "full_content": "Most people understand karma as 'what goes around comes around' — a vague moral accounting system. Jain philosophy says something far more radical: karma is physical. It is actual subtle matter (karma pudgala) that attaches to the soul.\n\nEvery action of mind, speech, and body generates vibrations (yoga). These vibrations attract karma particles from the surrounding space. The particles then bind to the soul, and the nature of the bondage depends on four factors: what type of karma binds (prakriti), how long it will last (sthiti), how intensely it will manifest (anubhag), and how many particles bind (pradesha).\n\nThere are eight fundamental types of karma, divided into two categories. The four Ghati (destructive) karmas directly obscure the soul's inherent qualities: Jnanavarniya blocks knowledge, Darshanavarniya blocks perception, Mohaniya creates delusion, and Antaraya obstructs the soul's energy. The four Aghati (non-destructive) karmas affect the embodied experience: Vedaniya determines pleasure and pain, Nama determines the body and physical traits, Gotra determines family status, and Ayushya determines lifespan.\n\nThe Ghati karmas are the real enemies. When all four are destroyed — even while still living — the soul achieves Kevala Jnana (omniscience). This is the state of the Arihant. The remaining Aghati karmas continue until the body's natural death, at which point they too fall away and the soul achieves Moksha.\n\nThis material conception of karma is what makes Jain ethics so precise. It's not about 'being a good person' in some vague sense. Every thought, every word, every action has specific, measurable karmic consequences. The system is mechanical, not judgmental. There is no god distributing rewards and punishments. The universe operates on karmic physics.",
