    "tagline": "Influx, stoppage, shedding — the three mechanisms that determine your karmic trajectory.",
    "summary": "Asrav is the inflow of karma. Samvar is stopping that flow. Nirjara is burning off what's already there. Master these three processes and you master the path to liberation.",
    "full_content": "These three tattvas are the operational heart of Jain karma theory. If karma is the disease, Asrav is how you catch it, Samvar is how you stop catching more, and Nirjara is how you cure what you've already got.\n\nAsrav (Influx): Every activity creates vibrations — physical actions, spoken words, mental thoughts. These vibrations attract karma particles from the surrounding space. The more intense the activity, the greater the influx. But activity alone doesn't determine the damage. It's the combination of activity and passion (kashay) that creates binding.\n\nThere are two types of Asrav: Bhava Asrav (the psychic cause — the passions and mental states that initiate the process) and Dravya Asrav (the material result — the actual particles flowing in). A person acting with complete equanimity, even if physically active, generates minimal binding karma. A person sitting still but seething with rage generates intense binding karma.\n\nSamvar (Stoppage): This is the discipline of reducing and stopping the inflow. The Jain tradition identifies specific practices: Samiti (carefulness in walking, speaking, eating, handling objects, and disposal of waste), Gupti (restraint of mind, speech, and body), Dharma (ten forms of righteous conduct including forgiveness, humility, and honesty), Anupreksha (twelve reflections on the nature of reality), and Parishaha Jaya (endurance of twenty-two hardships without losing equanimity).\n\nNirjara (Shedding): Even after stopping new inflow, the soul carries accumulated karma from beginningless time. This must be destroyed. Sakama Nirjara happens naturally when karma matures and bears fruit — you experience its result and it falls away. Akama Nirjara is deliberate — through austerities (tapas), meditation, and spiritual practice, karma is burned off before it would naturally mature.\n\nThe path to liberation is exactly this: maximize Samvar, practice Nirjara, minimize Asrav. When all accumulated karma is shed and no new karma binds, the soul is free.",
    "key_terms": [
      {
        "term": "Bhava Asrav",
        "meaning": "Psychic influx — the mental states and passions that attract karma"
      },
      {
        "term": "Samiti",
        "meaning": "Carefulness — five practices of mindful activity that reduce karmic influx"
      },
      {
        "term": "Tapas",
        "meaning": "Austerity — practices that accelerate the shedding of accumulated karma"
      }
    ],
