    "id": "leshya",
    "sanskrit": "लेश्या",
    "title": "Leshya",
    "category": "Karma System",
    "tagline": "The six colorations of the soul — a mirror of your inner state.",
    "summary": "Leshya describes six psychic colorations of the soul, ranging from black (most harmful) to white (most pure), reflecting the soul's current spiritual and emotional state.",
    "full_content": "Leshya is one of Jain philosophy's most vivid concepts — the idea that the soul's inner state has a 'color,' a vibration that reflects its current spiritual condition.\n\nThe six Leshyas, from worst to best:\n\nKrishna (Black) Leshya — the soul in its most degraded state. Characterized by cruelty, destructiveness, and complete disregard for other beings. A person in Krishna Leshya would destroy an entire tree just to eat one fruit.\n\nNeel (Blue) Leshya — characterized by laziness, dishonesty, and selfishness. A person in Neel Leshya would cut down most of a tree to get fruit, showing reckless disregard.\n\nKapot (Grey) Leshya — characterized by anger, complaints, and irritability. A person in Kapot Leshya would cut a major branch to get fruit — excessive but not maximal destruction.\n\nTejo (Red/Fiery) Leshya — the turning point. Characterized by moderate desires and some degree of self-awareness. A person in Tejo Leshya would cut only a small branch — taking what they need without excess.\n\nPadma (Yellow/Lotus) Leshya — characterized by discipline, ethical conduct, and spiritual aspiration. A person in Padma Leshya would pick only the ripe fruits they need, leaving the tree undisturbed.\n\nShukla (White) Leshya — the purest state. Characterized by equanimity, compassion, and complete non-violence. A person in Shukla Leshya would only pick fruits that have already fallen — taking nothing by force, disturbing nothing.\n\nThe tree analogy is traditional and powerful. It reveals that Leshya is not about what you do in the abstract — it's about how much unnecessary harm accompanies your actions. Everyone needs to eat. The question is: how much destruction do you cause in the process?\n\nLeshya is not permanent. It changes moment to moment based on thoughts, intentions, and actions. The goal of spiritual practice is to progressively shift from the darker Leshyas toward Shukla Leshya.",
