    "id": "charitra",
    "sanskrit": "चारित्र",
    "title": "Charitra",
    "category": "The Path",
    "tagline": "Right conduct — where philosophy becomes practice, and practice becomes liberation.",
    "summary": "Charitra is the ethical dimension of the path — the five great vows (Mahavrats) and their application in daily life. It is philosophy translated into lived discipline.",
    "full_content": "Charitra — right conduct — is where Jain philosophy meets the ground. You can believe perfectly (Samyak Darshan) and know everything (Samyak Jnana), but without Charitra, liberation remains theoretical.\n\nThe foundation of Charitra is the five vows. For monks and nuns, these are the Mahavrats (great vows) — absolute and without exception. For laypeople, they are the Anuvrats (small vows) — practiced to the degree that life permits.\n\nAhimsa (Non-violence) — the first and foremost. Not just refraining from killing, but avoiding harm in thought, word, and deed. This extends to not causing others to harm, and not approving of harm done by others. Jain non-violence is the most comprehensive ethical principle in any philosophical tradition.\n\nSatya (Truth) — speaking truthfully, but with an important caveat: truth should not be spoken if it causes harm. If truth and non-violence conflict, non-violence prevails.\n\nAsteya (Non-stealing) — not taking anything that is not freely given. This extends beyond physical theft to using things without permission, exploiting labor, and taking more than your share.\n\nBrahmacharya (Celibacy/Chastity) — for monks, complete celibacy. For laypeople, fidelity and restraint. The underlying principle is non-attachment to sensory pleasures.\n\nAparigraha (Non-possessiveness) — limiting possessions, reducing attachment to material things. For monks, this means owning virtually nothing. For laypeople, it means setting deliberate limits on wealth, possessions, and consumption.\n\nThese vows are not arbitrary rules. Each one directly addresses a mechanism of karmic bondage. Violence, dishonesty, theft, sensual indulgence, and possessiveness are the primary channels through which heavy karma flows in. The vows are surgical — they target the exact behaviors that generate the most binding karma.\n\nCharitra also includes practices like equanimity (samayik), confession and repentance (pratikraman), and dietary discipline. Together, they form a complete ethical architecture for the journey toward liberation.",
