    "id": "pratikraman",
    "sanskrit": "प्रतिक्रमण",
    "title": "Pratikraman",
    "category": "The Path",
    "tagline": "The daily practice of looking back, acknowledging harm, and resolving to do better.",
    "summary": "Pratikraman is the formal practice of introspection, confession, and repentance — reviewing one's actions, acknowledging transgressions, and recommitting to the path.",
    "full_content": "Pratikraman literally means 'to turn back' — turning back from harmful actions toward righteous conduct. It is the most important daily practice in Jain life.\n\nThe practice involves systematic self-review. What did I do today that caused harm? What did I say that was untrue or hurtful? What did I think that was driven by anger, pride, deceit, or greed? For each transgression identified, the practitioner formally acknowledges it, expresses genuine repentance (prayashchitta), and resolves not to repeat it.\n\nPratikraman operates at multiple time scales. Devasi Pratikraman is done twice daily — morning and evening. Pakshi Pratikraman is done fortnightly. Chaumasi Pratikraman every four months. And Samvatsari Pratikraman — the most significant — is done annually during Paryushana, the most important Jain festival.\n\nDuring Samvatsari Pratikraman, Jains seek forgiveness from all beings — not just people they've knowingly harmed, but all beings they may have harmed unknowingly. The universal request for forgiveness — 'Micchami Dukkadam' (may all my improper actions be forgiven) — is sent to friends, family, and the entire world.\n\nPratikraman is not guilt. Jainism draws a clear distinction between guilt (which is a form of attachment to the past) and genuine repentance (which acknowledges the error and moves forward). The emphasis is not on punishment but on correction. You cannot undo past karma, but you can stop generating new harmful karma and accelerate the shedding of old karma.\n\nIn practice, Pratikraman includes recitation of specific sutras, contemplation of the transgressions against the five vows, and a formal declaration of remorse. It is both deeply personal and communally practiced.\n\nThis practice embodies a core Jain insight: spiritual progress is not linear. You will stumble. You will transgress. The question is not whether you will fall, but whether you will get up, acknowledge the fall honestly, and keep walking.",
