    "id": "gunsthanaks",
    "sanskrit": "गुणस्थानक",
    "title": "Gunsthanaks",
    "category": "The Path",
    "tagline": "The fourteen stages of spiritual progress — from total delusion to total liberation.",
    "summary": "The fourteen Gunsthanaks map the soul's entire spiritual journey from complete ignorance to omniscience, providing a precise metric for spiritual development.",
    "full_content": "The Gunsthanaks are Jain philosophy's most precise contribution to spiritual science — a fourteen-stage scale that maps the soul's journey from complete delusion to complete liberation. No other tradition has attempted this level of specificity.\n\nStage 1: Mithyatva — Wrong belief. The soul has no right faith. It may be religious, moral, even ascetic — but without Samyaktva, it is at the lowest stage.\n\nStage 2: Sasvadana — Taste of right faith. A brief, unstable experience of Samyaktva that quickly fades. Like tasting something sweet and losing it.\n\nStage 3: Mishra — Mixed. Right and wrong faith alternate. The soul oscillates between clarity and confusion.\n\nStage 4: Avirata Samyak Dristi — Right faith without vows. The soul has stable Samyaktva but hasn't yet adopted the vows. This is a pivotal stage — the first genuine spiritual accomplishment.\n\nStage 5: Desh Virata — Partial vows. The soul takes the Anuvrats — the householder's vows. It lives ethically within worldly life.\n\nStage 6: Pramatta Virata — Complete vows with occasional lapses. The soul has taken Mahavrats but sometimes falters due to negligence (pramad).\n\nStage 7: Apramatta Virata — Complete vows without negligence. Constant vigilance. No lapses.\n\nStages 8-10 involve progressive suppression and elimination of increasingly subtle passions. These are advanced states of deep meditation.\n\nStage 11: Upashanta Moha — Delusion suppressed. All passions are temporarily suppressed (not yet destroyed). This is a precarious stage — if suppression fails, the soul can fall back.\n\nStage 12: Kshina Moha — Delusion destroyed. All passions have been permanently eliminated. This is irreversible.\n\nStage 13: Sayoga Kevali — Omniscience with bodily activity. This is the state of the Arihant — all Ghati karmas destroyed, infinite knowledge attained, but still embodied. The Tirthankars teach from this stage.\n\nStage 14: Ayoga Kevali — Omniscience without activity. The final moments before the soul sheds the body and all remaining Aghati karmas. This stage lasts only the time it takes to speak five short syllables. Then — Moksha.\n\nThe Gunsthanaks accomplish something remarkable: they make spiritual progress measurable. Not in terms of good deeds counted or mantras recited, but in terms of which passions have been conquered and which karmas have been destroyed.",
